            </row>
          </tabular>

        </table>

      </solution>
    </example>

    <example xml:id="ex_no_limit2">
      <title>The Function Grows Without Bound</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Explore why <m>\ds\lim_{x\to 1} 1/(x-1)^2</m> does not exist.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          A graph and table of <m>f(x) = 1/(x-1)^2</m> are given in <xref ref="fig_nolimit2">Figures</xref>
          and <xref ref="table_nolimit2"></xref>, respectively.
          Both show that as <m>x</m> approaches 1, <m>f(x)</m> grows larger and larger.
        </p>

        <figure xml:id="fig_nolimit2">
          <caption>Observing no limit as <m>x\to 1</m> in <xref ref="ex_no_limit2">Example</xref>.</caption>
          <img src="figures/fignolimit2"/>
        </figure>

        <table xml:id="table_nolimit2">
          <caption>Values of <m>f(x)</m> near <m>x=1</m> in <xref ref="ex_no_limit2">Example</xref>.</caption>
          <tabular>
            <row>
              <cell><m>x</m></cell>
              <cell><m>f(x)</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row bottom="minor">
              <cell></cell>
              <cell></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell>0.9</cell>
              <cell>100.</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell>0.99</cell>
              <cell>10000.</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell>0.999</cell>
              <cell><m>1.\times 10^6</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell>1.001</cell>
              <cell><m>1.\times 10^6</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell>1.01</cell>
              <cell>10000.</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell>1.1</cell>
              <cell>100.</cell>
            </row>
          </tabular>

        </table>

        <p>
          We can deduce this on our own,
          without the aid of the graph and table.
          If <m>x</m> is near 1, then <m>(x-1)^2</m> is very small, and:
          <me>
            \frac{1}{\text{ very small number } } = \text{ very large number } 
          </me>.
        </p>

        <p>
          Since <m>f(x)</m> is not approaching a single number, we conclude that
          <me>
            \lim_{x\to 1}\frac{1}{(x-1)^2}
          </me>
          does not exist.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <example xml:id="ex_no_limit3">
      <title>The Function Oscillates</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Explore why <m>\ds\lim_{x\to 0}\sin(1/x)</m> does not exist.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Two graphs of <m>f(x) = \sin(1/x)</m> are given in <xref ref="fig_nolimit3">Figures</xref>.
          <xref ref="fig_nolimit3">Figure</xref>(a) shows <m>f(x)</m> on the interval <m>[-1,1]</m>;
          notice how <m>f(x)</m> seems to oscillate near <m>x=0</m>.
          One might think that despite the oscillation,
          as <m>x</m> approaches 0, <m>f(x)</m> approaches 0.
          However, <xref ref="fig_nolimit3">Figure</xref>(b) zooms in on <m>\sin(1/x)</m>,
          on the interval <m>[-0.1,0.1]</m>.
          Here the oscillation is even more pronounced.
          Finally, in the table in <xref ref="fig_nolimit3">Figure</xref>(c),
          we see <m>\sin(1/x)</m> evaluated for values of <m>x</m> near 0.
          As <m>x</m> approaches 0, <m>f(x)</m> does not appear to approach any value.
        </p>

        <p>
          It can be shown that in reality,
          as <m>x</m> approaches 0, <m>\sin(1/x)</m> takes on all values between <m>-1</m> and 1 infinitely many times!
          Because of this oscillation,
        </p>

        <p>
          <m>\ds\lim_{x\to 0}\sin(1/x)</m> does not exist.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
